		<div class="blog-header">
			<h2 class="blog-title">
					<a class="blog-title-link blog-link" href="//mackayenglish.weebly.com/blog/modern-propaganda-compared-to-that-within-animal-farm-by-logan-4a">Modern Propaganda compared to that within Animal Farm by: logan (4A)</a>

			</h2>
			<p class="blog-date">
					<span class="date-text">
		5/5/2015
	</span>

			</p>
			<p class="blog-comments">
					<a href="//mackayenglish.weebly.com/blog/modern-propaganda-compared-to-that-within-animal-farm-by-logan-4a#comments" class="blog-link">
		1 Comment
	</a>

			</p>
		</div>
	
		<div class="blog-separator">&nbsp;</div>
	
		<div class="blog-content">
				<div><div class="wsite-multicol"><div class="wsite-multicol-table-wrap" style="margin:0 -15px;"> 	<table class="wsite-multicol-table"> 		<tbody class="wsite-multicol-tbody"> 			<tr class="wsite-multicol-tr"> 				<td class="wsite-multicol-col" style="width:43.833780160858%; padding:0 15px;"> 					 						  <span class='imgPusher' style='float:left;height:0px'></span><span style='display: table;z-index:10;width:auto;position:relative;float:left;max-width:100%;;clear:left;margin-top:0px;*margin-top:0px'><a><img src="/uploads/5/0/9/4/50940509/8513182.jpg?232" style="margin-top: 5px; margin-bottom: 10px; margin-left: 0px; margin-right: 10px; border-width:1px;padding:3px; max-width:100%" alt="Picture" class="galleryImageBorder wsite-image" /></a><span style="display: table-caption; caption-side: bottom; font-size: 90%; margin-top: -10px; margin-bottom: 10px; text-align: center;" class="wsite-caption"></span></span> <div class="paragraph" style="text-align:justify;display:block;"><span style='text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(82, 79, 86); '><span style="text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(82, 79, 86); "><span style="text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(82, 79, 86); "><span style="text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(82, 79, 86); "><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><span style=""></span><br /><span style=""></span><span style="">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><span style="">Corporations such as Wal-Mart, Nike, Apple, ect. put out advertisements to promote their products every year. With these advertisements is usually some sort of slogan or catchphrase to describe themselves or those who use their products. For example: Wal-Mart&rsquo;s &ldquo;Save Money. Live Better&rdquo; slogan is used so that consumers almost grow an emotional bond with the company. Wal-Mart want to be seen more as a &ldquo;Family Friend&rdquo; than a major world corporation. This use of slogan corresponds with those used in </span><span style="">Animal Farm</span><span style="">. &ldquo;Four Legs Good. Two Legs Bad.&rdquo; was the slogan created by Napoleon that the animals on the farm stood by for a large portion of the novel. The slogan was used to bring the animals on the farm together and give them a common enemy: Man.</span><br /><span style=""></span><br /><span style=""></span><span style="">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><span style="">Another popular form of propaganda used by major corporations is one known as &ldquo;Glittering Generalities&rdquo;. This form of propaganda is used to create favorable emotions. This can be done by using specific words: freedom, values, family, ect. An example of this use in society is seen by Coca-Cola's "Life" product. In advertisements for this new beverage, family values are shown and used to sell the product. "Glittering Generalities" can be seen all throughout </span><span style="">Animal Farm. </span><span style="">The commandments scrawled on the wall of the barn were written to keep the values of Animal Farm alive. At the same time however they were written vaguely enough that the could potentially be changed which they are indeed. </span><br /><span style=""></span><br /><span style=""></span><span style=""> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;Propaganda is associated with totalitarian governments as a way to promote the government. It is often used that way, but propaganda has a wider definition than that. George Orwell's </span><span style="">Animal Farm</span><span style=""> may having been written almost 70 years ago is still very much so relevant to modern society. This relevance can easily be seen simply by comparing the propaganda in the novel to that in modern society. The correlation between the two are fairly similar. </span></span></span></span></span></div> <hr style="width:100%;clear:both;visibility:hidden;"></hr>   					 				</td>				<td class="wsite-multicol-col" style="width:56.166219839142%; padding:0 15px;"> 					 						  <div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;"><span style='text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(82, 79, 86); '><span style="text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(82, 79, 86); "><span style="text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(82, 79, 86); "><span style=""><span style=""><span style=""><span style="">Propaganda plays a very dominating role within the plot of George Orwell&rsquo;s </span><span style="">Animal Farm</span><span style="">.  While propaganda is usually seen as a product of &nbsp;governments or  political groups, propaganda also plays a very present role in todays  modern society. From the advertisements and slogans seen by corporations  on TV and billboards, propaganda is seen by the public on a daily  basis. In </span><span style="">Animal Farm</span><span style="">,  Squealer is a sort of propaganda machine. Constantly spouting lies that  Napoleon and his government want the farm to believe. Private  corporations put out numerous advertisements every year that follow the  same path as Squealer&rsquo;s speeches fairly closely. They usually are not  politically based, but they use propaganda in a very similar way in  order to get the public to believe in their products and give them their  money.<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div>  <div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"> <a href='http://www.walmart.com'> <img src="/uploads/5/0/9/4/50940509/3808800.jpg?296" alt="Picture" style="width:296;max-width:100%" /> </a> <div style="display:block;font-size:90%"></div> </div></div>  <div class="wsite-spacer" style="height:50px;"></div>  <div><div class="wsite-image wsite-image-border-none " style="padding-top:10px;padding-bottom:10px;margin-left:0;margin-right:0;text-align:center"> <a> <img src="/uploads/5/0/9/4/50940509/4498108.jpeg?253" alt="Picture" style="width:253;max-width:100%" /> </a> <div style="display:block;font-size:90%"></div> </div></div>   					 				</td>			</tr> 		</tbody> 	</table> </div></div></div>  <div class="paragraph" style="text-align:left;"><span style='text-decoration:none; font-style:normal; font-weight:400; color:rgb(82, 79, 86); '>Orwell, George. <em style="">Animal Farm</em>. London: Penguin, 1946. Print. </span></div>

		</div>
	
	
